  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed — first 5 minutes are just waking up the legs. No pressure to hit pace yet.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic effort. You should be able to hold a full conversation. Heart rate should stay well below threshold — think 65–70% of max HR.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 5 minutes. Let your heart rate drift down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed beyond the easy first 5 minutes of the run itself. A few dynamic leg swings or ankle circles before you head out is plenty.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After the run, spend 5–10 minutes on light static stretching — calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings. Given your Achilles history, a gentle calf stretch and eccentric heel drop (off a step, slow and controlled) is a good habit to keep.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your aerobic foundation run for the week — the bread and butter of maintenance training. The goal is simply to accumulate easy aerobic stimulus without creating fatigue. Resist the urge to push the pace; the value here is in the consistency and the aerobic enzyme activity, not the speed. Your easy range is 5:22–5:56/km — anywhere in that window is perfect depending on how your legs feel coming off the weekend.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2Max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":251,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog for approximately 2 km. Include 4–6 strides of 20 seconds at interval pace in the final 2 minutes to prime the neuromuscular system before the hard work begins.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":251,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 1 km at interval pace (4:11/km). This is a controlled hard effort — not a sprint, not a race. You should feel like you could run one more rep at the end of the set, but it should be genuinely challenging. Take 90 seconds of easy jogging between each rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"90-second easy jog between each 1 km rep. Keep moving — don't stop completely. This active recovery helps clear lactate while keeping your cardiovascular system primed for the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":13,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog for approximately 1.5–2 km to bring heart rate down gradually. Don't skip this — it matters for recovery quality.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by dynamic drills: leg swings, high knees, butt kicks, and 4–6 x 20-second strides building to interval pace. This primes your cardiovascular and neuromuscular systems for the hard effort ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"1.5–2 km easy jog, then 5–10 minutes of static stretching. Pay particular attention to your left calf and Achilles — gentle calf stretch and eccentric heel drops off a step if you have one nearby.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Interval work at VO2Max pace is the most potent stimulus for improving your aerobic ceiling — and in maintenance, it keeps that ceiling from dropping. The 4:11/km target is your Daniels interval pace derived from your VDOT of 46.7. The key execution cue: these reps should feel hard but controlled. If you're gasping after rep 2, you've gone out too fast. If rep 5 feels easy, you held back too much. Aim for that sweet spot where rep 5 is genuinely tough but achievable with good form. This mirrors the session you completed on March 15th, which is a great sign — you already know what this feels like.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":356,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This run should feel almost embarrassingly easy. The slower end of your easy range (5:56/km) or even a touch slower is perfectly appropriate the day after intervals. Heart rate should stay below 65% of max HR. If your legs feel heavy or your HR is elevated, it's completely fine to shorten this to 4–5 km or swap for a walk.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed. Just ease into the run very gradually — the first kilometre is the warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Light stretching post-run. Eccentric calf work (heel drops) is encouraged given your Achilles history — 3 sets of 10 slow reps on each leg.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Recovery runs are one of the most underrated tools in a maintenance plan. Running at a genuinely easy effort the day after hard work flushes metabolic byproducts, maintains movement patterns, and adds aerobic volume without adding meaningful stress. The temptation is always to run faster than this — but the physiological value is specifically in the low intensity. Think of this as active recovery, not a workout. Your March 18th recovery run at 5:56/km is exactly the right model.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Tempo Run\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":54,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog. This is non-negotiable for tempo work — your lactate threshold system needs a few minutes of aerobic priming before it can operate efficiently at threshold pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":36,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"8 km continuous at threshold pace (4:28/km). This is comfortably hard — you could speak in short phrases but not hold a conversation. It should feel sustainable but purposeful. If you drift 5 seconds per km fast or slow, that's fine. If you're more than 10 seconds off, adjust.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":11,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2 km easy jog to bring heart rate down gradually. Don't stop abruptly after threshold work.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"2 km easy jog. You might include 2–3 short accelerations (20 seconds building toward threshold pace) in the final 400 m of the warmup to prime your legs for the effort ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2 km easy jog followed by 5–10 minutes of static stretching. Calf and Achilles attention as always.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold running is the cornerstone of maintaining marathon fitness. Running at your lactate threshold pace (4:28/km) teaches your body to clear lactate as fast as it produces it — which directly translates to being able to sustain marathon pace for longer. In a maintenance context, this session keeps your threshold from drifting upward (i.e., getting slower) without the heavy training load of a build phase. This mirrors your March 17th session, which you executed well. The 8 km at threshold is a solid, honest effort — not a race, not a jog.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":339,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":322,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease in gently. Your legs may carry some residual fatigue from Thursday's tempo — that's normal and expected.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":339,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable aerobic effort. Conversational pace throughout. If your legs feel heavy from the tempo, drift toward the slower end of your easy range (5:45–5:56/km) — that's the right call, not a compromise.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Wind down the final 5 minutes. Let your body signal what it needs.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup beyond the easy start of the run. Dynamic leg swings and ankle mobility before heading out is a good habit, especially mid-week.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Light stretching. This is a good day for a slightly longer post-run routine if you have time — 10–15 minutes of mobility work pays dividends over a maintenance block.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This Friday easy run serves two purposes: it adds aerobic volume to the week and it begins the gentle priming process for Sunday's long run. Keeping it genuinely easy is the key. There's no physiological benefit to pushing this run — the adaptation from Tuesday's intervals and Thursday's tempo is still happening, and easy running supports that process rather than interrupting it.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":118,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":356,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":339,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes very relaxed — let your body warm up naturally. Don't chase pace in the opening kilometres.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":98,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":356,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable long-run effort. Target 5:45–5:56/km throughout. The goal is time on feet and aerobic stimulus, not speed. If you feel good in the final 20–25 minutes, you might allow a very slight natural drift toward 5:30/km — but only if it feels genuinely effortless, not forced.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 10 minutes, ease off intentionally. Arrive home feeling like you could have run another 3–4 km — that's the right long-run finish.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed beyond the easy opening kilometres. Before you head out, 5 minutes of dynamic mobility — leg swings, hip circles, ankle rotations — is worthwhile, particularly for your left Achilles.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After the run: 5–10 minutes of walking, then 10–15 minutes of thorough static stretching. Calves, hip flexors, hamstrings, glutes. Eccentric heel drops (3 x 10 each leg) are strongly encouraged as ongoing Achilles maintenance. Hydrate and refuel within 30–45 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the anchor of your maintenance week. At 20 km, you're maintaining the aerobic base and muscular endurance that underpins your marathon fitness — without the fatigue cost of pushing into 22–24 km territory that a build phase would require. Running at 5:45–5:56/km keeps you in the fat-oxidation zone, which is exactly where long-run adaptation happens. Your recent long runs (20 km on March 20th, 21 km on March 13th) show you're handling this distance well — this week's session is about consistency, not progression. One practical note: given your 120-minute cap and your recent 21 km in 124 minutes, staying at 20 km keeps you comfortably within that window. If you feel strong, resist the urge to extend — the value of the long run in maintenance is the stimulus, not the distance PR.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
